## Part 1 — Agentic Loop + Structured Extraction (15 min)

### Concepts: agentic loop lifecycle, JSON schema, tool_choice, required vs nullable fields

### Your task

Build the core grading loop. On each API call, inspect `stop_reason` to decide whether
to execute the requested tool or return the final result. Use `tool_use` with a forced
`tool_choice` to guarantee structured output.

**Schema fields:**

| Field | Type | Required? | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `overall_score` | integer | yes | 1–10 |
| `content_score` | integer | yes | 1–10: quality of argument and evidence |
| `structure_score` | integer | yes | 1–10: organisation, paragraphing, flow |
| `language_score` | integer | yes | 1–10: vocabulary, grammar, sentence variety |
| `strengths` | array of strings | yes | Min 1 item; specific to this essay |
| `weaknesses` | array of strings | yes | Min 1 item; specific to this essay |
| `improvement_suggestion` | string | yes | One concrete, actionable next step |
| `improvement_example` | string or null | no | A rewritten sentence/phrase from the essay — null if no clear example applies |
| `grade_justified` | boolean | yes | Does the overall_score reflect the component scores? |

**Key exam concept:** `improvement_example` is nullable because not every essay has
a sentence that illustrates the improvement clearly. Making it required would pressure
the model to fabricate an example. `strengths` and `weaknesses` are required arrays —
never null — because every essay has both.

